name: Kenya Protest LIVE: Police Block Roads To Nairobi on Anniversary of Pro-Democracy Protests | N18G
description:
Kenya Protest LIVE: Protests in Nairobi, Kenya on Anniversary of Historic Pro-Democracy March | CNBC TV18
Nairobi, Kenya - Protests expected in Kenya on anniversary of historic pro-democracy march. Known as Saba Saba (Seven Seven), July 7 is remembered as the day Kenyans took to the streets in 1990 demanding multi-party democracy. This year, the anniversary is set against a backdrop of rising public anger over police brutality, abductions of activists, corruption, and a deepening economic crisis. Protesters are expected to gather in the Central Business District, with a strong police presence anticipated.
Kenyans hold a protest in Nairobi against police brutality, as anger has reignited over the longstanding issue by the death of blogger Albert Ojwang in police custody and the close-range shooting by police of vendor Boniface Kariuki during protests for Ojwang mid-June. Human rights groups have long called for action over illegal arrests, detentions and torture of government critics in Kenya. President William Ruto has vowed to end police brutality and said no enforced disappearances would happen during his administration. But Ruto's interior minister told police to â€œshoot on sightâ€ anyone who approaches police stations during protests, after five police stations were torched.

Kenya descends into CHAOS as MASSIVE violent protests erupt against police brutality
description:
Thousands of protesters took to the streets in Nairobi on Wednesday, clashing with police over issues of police brutality and government corruption, as demonstrations spread nationwide.

The confrontations saw police deploying tear gas and using batons, resulting in several injuries. These protests coincide with the one-year anniversary of anti-tax demonstrations that led to 60 deaths and left 20 individuals missing.

The unrest has now extended to major cities such as Mombasa, Kisumu, Nakuru, and Nyahururu, evolving into demands for the president's resignation over allegations of poor governance.

Kenyan youth are particularly dissatisfied with the current administration, citing corruption, a rising cost of living, and police brutality, further fuelled by the recent death of a blogger in custody.

Public anger has been intensified by the close-range shooting of a civilian during recent demonstrations.
